    "verse_type": "verse",
    "chunk_id": "747b9fcb1b7d4e71"
  },
  {
    "text": "Where one asleep desires no desire whatsoever, sees no dream whatsoever, that is deep sleep. The sleeping state, having become one, a consolidated mass of cognition, consisting of bliss, enjoying bliss, whose face is thought, the Prajna, is the third quarter.",
    "scripture": "Mandukya Upanishad",
    "tradition": "hindu_vedanta",
    "chapter": 1,
    "verse": 5,
    "translator": "Max Müller",
    "year": 1884,
    "language": "en",
    "license_tier": "A",
    "source_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/index.htm",
    "themes": [],
    "sanskrit": null,
    "speaker": null,
    "chapter_name": null,
    "commentary_source": null,
    "chunk_type": "verse",
    "verse_type": "verse",
    "chunk_id": "a9320ae84fa015d1"
  },
  {
    "text": "This is the lord of all, this is the omniscient, this is the inner controller, this is the source of all, this is the beginning and end of all beings.",
    "scripture": "Mandukya Upanishad",
    "tradition": "hindu_vedanta",
    "chapter": 1,
    "verse": 6,
    "translator": "Max Müller",
    "year": 1884,
    "language": "en",
    "license_tier": "A",
    "source_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/index.htm",
    "themes": [],
    "sanskrit": null,
    "speaker": null,
    "chapter_name": null,
    "commentary_source": null,
    "chunk_type": "verse",
    "verse_type": "verse",
    "chunk_id": "38e612a4db54e0b2"
  },
  {
    "text": "Not that which is conscious of the internal world, nor that which is conscious of the external world, nor that which is conscious of both, nor that which is a consolidated mass of consciousness, nor which is all cognitive, nor which is not cognitive — unseen, with which there can be no dealing, ungraspable, having no distinctive mark, non-thinkable, that cannot be designated, the essence of the assurance of which is the state of being one with the Self, the cessation of the visible world, the peaceful, the benign, the non-dual — they consider to be the fourth. He is the Atman; he should be discerned.",
    "scripture": "Mandukya Upanishad",
    "tradition": "hindu_vedanta",
    "chapter": 1,
    "verse": 7,
    "translator": "Max Müller",
    "year": 1884,
    "language": "en",
    "license_tier": "A",
    "source_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/index.htm",
    "themes": [
      "atman"
    ],
    "sanskrit": null,
    "speaker": null,
    "chapter_name": null,
    "commentary_source": null,
    "chunk_type": "verse",
    "verse_type": "verse",
    "chunk_id": "54ff695d916fdb79"
  },
  {
    "text": "This same Atman, as regards its syllabic nature, is Om; as regards its syllables, Om has three measures (matras) — a, u, m.",
    "scripture": "Mandukya Upanishad",
    "tradition": "hindu_vedanta",
    "chapter": 1,
    "verse": 8,
    "translator": "Max Müller",
    "year": 1884,
    "language": "en",
    "license_tier": "A",
    "source_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/index.htm",
    "themes": [
      "atman"
    ],
    "sanskrit": null,
    "speaker": null,
    "chapter_name": null,
    "commentary_source": null,
    "chunk_type": "verse",
    "verse_type": "verse",
    "chunk_id": "1760c2bdb568b3b3"
  },
  {
    "text": "The waking state, the Vaishvanara, is the first measure a, from the root ap (to obtain), or from being the first (adimattva). He who thus knows obtains all desires and becomes first.",
    "scripture": "Mandukya Upanishad",
    "tradition": "hindu_vedanta",
    "chapter": 1,
    "verse": 9,
    "translator": "Max Müller",
    "year": 1884,
    "language": "en",
    "license_tier": "A",
    "source_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/index.htm",
    "themes": [
      "knowledge"
    ],
    "sanskrit": null,
    "speaker": null,
    "chapter_name": null,
    "commentary_source": null,
    "chunk_type": "verse",
    "verse_type": "verse",
    "chunk_id": "a7a8e784226602b6"
  },
  {
    "text": "The sleeping state, the Taijasa, is the second measure u, from the root ut (to exalt), or from being in the middle. He who thus knows exalts the continuity of knowledge, and is treated equally (by all), and no one ignorant of Brahman is born in his family.",
    "scripture": "Mandukya Upanishad",
    "tradition": "hindu_vedanta",
    "chapter": 1,
    "verse": 10,
    "translator": "Max Müller",
    "year": 1884,
    "language": "en",
    "license_tier": "A",
    "source_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/index.htm",
    "themes": [
      "brahman",
      "knowledge",
      "creation"
    ],
    "sanskrit": null,
    "speaker": null,
    "chapter_name": null,
    "commentary_source": null,
    "chunk_type": "verse",
    "verse_type": "verse",
    "chunk_id": "0fcbd0336116c6a1"
  },
  {
    "text": "The deep sleep state, the Prajna, is the third measure m, from the root mi (to erect), or from ma (to measure). He who thus knows erects this world and they merge in him.",
    "scripture": "Mandukya Upanishad",
    "tradition": "hindu_vedanta",
    "chapter": 1,
    "verse": 11,
    "translator": "Max Müller",
    "year": 1884,
    "language": "en",
    "license_tier": "A",
    "source_url": "https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/index.htm",
    "themes": [
      "knowledge"
    ],
    "sanskrit": null,
    "speaker": null,
    "chapter_name": null,
    "commentary_source": null,
    "chunk_type": "verse",
    "verse_type": "verse",
    "chunk_id": "5abd478768dc8eaf"
  },
  {
    "text": "The fourth is without a measure, with which there can be no dealing, the cessation of the phenomenal world, the blissful, the non-dual, thus Om is the Atman indeed. He who knows this merges with the Self. END OF THE MANDUKYA UPANISHAD",
    "scripture": "Mandukya Upanishad",
    "tradition": "hindu_vedanta",
